            "answer_text": "Did you hear something about a \"hill\" called Mt. Pel\u00e9e? It was plugged by a 700 m long stone needle. And she was erupted. The result was a quite interesting phenomenon. A cloud, moving fast as a TGV, heated to several hundred grad celsius and carriing large amount of different size pebble. It reached a small city within minutes, leaving 3 survivor of the 30.000+ population.Other volcanos simply explode in such situation.The volcanos built usually not from solid stone. They are layers of solidified lava and loose ashes. The bottom of the craters is usually solid rock, so in case of higher volcanoes, like Etna in Sicilly the main crater rarely flood lava. But since the raising magma make a solid push to the sides of lava channels, it usually push through the side of the volcano, creating new side craters (called parasite crater). Other volcanos, having more gaseous magma, creating stronger and more sudden push to the sides on the crater, erupting explosively.So simply cover the top of the crater results nothing. Drilling a hole to the magmachamber, and let the accumulating gases and lava has an easy and continuous outflow could reduce the size of eruptions effectively. But currently we have no technology that could survive in the circumstances of magmachamber without destruction or plugging. But at least, we can tell, the volcano is getting ready to erupt, or not. ",
