            "answer_text": "The eruption of Mt Taupo ~25,000 BC was large enough to not only completely destroy the mountain, but also form the second largest lake in Oceania. The eruption of Tarawera in 1886 was similar, leveling the mountain and creating a rift in the earth 17km long. Volcanoes play on their terms, and they don't play nice. As mentioned in other replies, plugging the top would make things worse. Think of filling up a water balloon; no matter how thick the skin is it will eventually burst, and the more water in it at the time, the worse it will be. The only way to fix this is to either apply a greater pressure from the outside than there is on the inside, or to relieve pressure inside by putting small holes in it and relieving pressure. Most vents are already capped by stone, and simply blow open when erupting. If you were to cap it with a stronger and more heat resistant material (after you invent one that could withstand such conditions), then the volcano would simply blow through the earth around it. You would in theory need to surround the entire vent, magna chamber, and all vents coming of it with your new material. I'll be impressed if you manage such a feat. ",
