            "answer_text": "Volcanoes that are plugged shut are by far the more dangerous kind.  If lava flows freely, because it has low viscosity (i.e. it's 'thin' or 'watery'), you have a lava flow to deal with, but that's not too bad. Yes it's dangerous, but you know where it is, and even if it changes course you have time to move out of the way.  Some volcanoes get plugged up, because the lava is so viscous and slow-flowing that it cools and hardens in the mouth of the volcano, or because the caldera collapses. This is bad. If the lava can't flow out, it builds up pressure. Think of blowing up a balloon. Unless the balloon is leaky, pressure builds up until the rubber can't take the strain, and BANG! the balloon pops, with a noise loud enough to startle you badly, perhaps sending shreds of rubber flying through the air. Now scale it up a bit. Instead of your breath you have the force of millions of tons of molten rock. The mountain can take much more strain than a balloon, but it has limits. The flanks of a volcano can bulge by tens of metres, until the pressure is too much -- and now the lava bursts out, not in a manageable trickle but an explosive fountain; and instead of a few shreds of balloon rubber, thousands of tons of rock is blown to powder in a shower of rocks and superheated ash that rushes down the mountainside in a deadly cloud -- this, not lava, is what moves fast enough to bury cities in its path, burning anything living in its path. It's a bit louder than a popped balloon, too. When the famous volcano Krakatau exploded, in 1883, the explosion was heard 3,000 miles away. It launched about 25 cubic kilometres of rock into the air (picture a cube of rock six miles to a side, now pulverise it), which lingered in the atmosphere, lowered the average surface temperature of the Earth by 1.2 degrees Celsius, and upset global weather systems for five years. The pressure wave circled the globe three times. In short, it would not be a good idea to plug up a volcano. ",
