                "name": "Pamela B. Zohar",
                "href": "/profile/Pamela-B-Zohar"
            },
            "answer_text": "First, you would have to find something that wouldn't melt from the heat of the lava - and something that wouldn't be torn apart by the force of the eruption (which is a kind of strong explosive force).If you found such a substance and placed it over the top of the volcano - THEN -  The lava would force itself out of the volcano through the cracks it would create along the sides. So all you would do is move the location where the lava leaves the ground, which isn't terrifically helpful. Iceland has had some success with building cement walls to redirect an existing lava flow away from houses, and using fire hoses to cool off the surface of a lava flow to slow it down and help change its course, at Haimey, but most such attempts have mixed success at best.:How do you stop the flow of lava? - BBC News ",
